**Iran-Backed Groups Vow to Retaliate Against Israel After Leaders' Deaths**
Iranian-backed groups in the Middle East, including Hamas in Palestine, Hezbollah in Lebanon, and Houthi rebels in Yemen, have vowed to retaliate against Israel after the leaders of Hamas and Hezbollah were killed. Abdul Malik al-Huthi, leader of the Houthi rebels, said in a speech that they would take military action against Israel in response to the killing of Ismail Haniyeh, leader of Hamas, in Tehran. 'It will have to be a military response to these crimes, which are heinous and deadly, and are a clear stigmatization of Israel,' he said. Houthi rebels have been supported by the Iranian government and have carried out repeated attacks on shipping vessels in the Red Sea, which they claim are in support of the Palestinian people. In the past month, one Israeli was killed in a drone attack by Houthi rebels in Tel Aviv. Haniyeh was designated as a terrorist by the United States and an international war crimes tribunal issued an arrest warrant for him for war crimes and crimes against humanity for his role in Hamas's attacks on Israel in October 7. Hezbollah also plans to give a 'real response' to Israel for killing Fuad Shukr, a leader of Hezbollah's operations against Israel in southern Lebanon. Hassan Nasrallah, leader of Hezbollah, said in a statement that they would 'give a real response, not a symbolic one.' Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, the supreme leader of Iran, has threatened 'severe punishment' for the killing of Haniyeh. 'With this action, the Zionist regime has laid the groundwork for severe punishment for itself and we must seek revenge for his blood where he was killed on the territory of the Islamic Republic of Iran,' he said in a statement. Hamas has also said that the killing of Haniyeh will not go unpunished.
