Israel's Foreign Minister, Israel Katz, described the airstrikes by the country's military against the Yemeni city of Al Hudayda as a blow to an Iranian-backed terrorist organization. Katz stated that Israel will attack any enemy that attacks it first. He also called on the international community to 'maximize sanctions against Iran', claiming that under its direction, the Houthis are severely damaging freedom of the seas and commercial routes. The Israeli Defense Forces (IDF) reported that they had bombed Al Hudayda, which was the first Israeli attack on Houthi targets in Yemen. The airstrikes were in response to 'hundreds of attacks carried out against the State of Israel in recent months', according to the IDF. The attacks resulted in two deaths and three injuries in Al Hudayda. Since the conflict between Israel and the Palestinian group Hamas began in October 2023, the Ansar Allah (Houthis) movement has shown solidarity with Hamas, launching missiles towards Israel. In November 2023, the Houthis also declared their decision to attack merchant ships related to Israel in the Gulf of Aden and the Red Sea in response to Israeli attacks on the Gaza Strip.
